<br>
Edward,<br>
   Jesus taught us to turn the other cheek and for slaves to succomb to their masters.  Think hard on that for awhile - these are teachings that are contrary to our human nature, but there is a great lesson to be learned that only a few will ever understand.  You are not &quot;wrong&quot; for serving your country, as Jed is not &quot;wrong&quot; (or cowardly) for his idealism - you are both on this earth simply experiencing different lessons. but your judgment is harsh and a bit reckless.  Realize that one does not have to find fault with another in order to justify their opposing stance. Aren't we all here with an ultimate objective to learn how to coexist peacefully and lovingly?  Isn't that an objective you would ideally wish for your children's future?  The power to make that change is within your grasp.  Try to keep that in mind when battling an opposing view - our children will never truly benefit from our individual battles and justifications (those are only for our own ego's satisfaction), but you can contribute greatly to their future happiness where you have helped to reach understanding with those who were once your enemy - isn't that the true lesson of Christianity?  Take the time to research the Native American respectful treatment of their non-warrior brothers.  An open mind is a powerful tool and it takes a brave soul to embark on that journey into that unknown and seemingly dangerous territory.  I have read on these threads your temptation to explore outside of the perimeter, but also your fear of losing yourself in the great ocean of possibilities.  The safety one feels with &quot;old ways&quot; is an illusion - your freedom is within the shores of expansion.  God bless and God's speed.  
